5. But there were dwelliny in Jerusalem. According to the Greek, “inliabiting.” That is to say, as the learned Mede ex- pounds it, “sojourning together3 ’³ including those who resorted together from other countries to celebrate the feasts of the Paschal Lamb and Pentecost3 for which purpose they took up their lodgings in the city, as is apparent by what follows. It is true that the Greek words denote a fixed and durable habitation. But among the Hellenists, whose dialect the writers of the New Testament imitate, they are indifferently made use of for a longer or shorter abiding in one place3 that is, as well for sojourning as for inhabiting: as the two following examples plainly prove from the translation of the Septuagint. The first is Gen. xxvii. 44, where the Greek word oz'kez‘n, and the Latin word habitare in the Vulgate version, signify to “tarry afew days.''
